Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Scudamore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Skidmore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Skidmore","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): of Norman origin, a variant of <b>Scudamore</b>, which most probably arises from a Norman French nickname for a knight who used a particular type of leather shield, from the unrecorded Norman French phrase, <i>escu de more</i> ‘Moor's shield’, a reference to a type of Moorish leather shield called an <i>adarga</i>, which was in widespread use not only in medieval Iberia and north Africa but also in Brittany.","History: The manor of Upton Scudamore in Wiltshire was held by Peter de Skydemore in 1216. The same manor was held by Godfrey Escudamore shortly after 1150. The Scudamore family claim descent from Ralph, recorded in Domesday Book (1086) as holder of <i>Opeton</i> (Upton), whose son was known as Reginald <i>Escudemor</i>."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":9,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alexander de Scudamore was born in 1026, in Kentchurch, Herefordshire, England, his father, Alexander de Scudamore, was 22 and his mother, Amelia Royce, was 18. He had at least 2 sons with Jane Catchman. He died in 1052, in Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1026–1052":"1026–1052","1030–1052":"1030–1052","1050–1120":"1050–1120","1052–1095":"1052–1095","1004–1052":"1004–1052","1008–Female":"1008–Surnud","1008":"1008","about 1052":"umbes 1052","1026":"1026","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1120":"1120","1052":"1052","1030":"1030","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","Kentchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Kentchurch, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England":"Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1026–1052":"1026–1052","1030–1052":"1030–1052","1050–1120":"1050–1120","1052–1095":"1052–1095","1004–1052":"1004–1052","1008–Female":"1008–Kuollut","1008":"1008","about 1052":"noin 1052","1026":"1026","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1120":"1120","1052":"1052","1030":"1030","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","Kentchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Kentchurch, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun